revision.text:
'''Choreomusicology''' is a [[portmanteau]] word joining the words [[choreology]] and [[musicology]].<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/14647893.2011.651116 | volume=13 | title=Music, dance and the total art work: choreomusicology in theory and practice | journal=Research in Dance Education | pages=5–24}}</ref><ref>https://www.academia.edu/4440413/Choreomusical_Discourse._The_relationship_between_Dance_and_Music</ref> As a discipline, choreomusicology emerged at the end of the twentieth century as a field of study concerned with the relationship between [[music]] and [[dance]]. More precisely, choreomusicology grew out of Euro-American performance traditions that considered musical composition and dance choreography as separate specialties. Not all performance genres separate music and dance into separate theoretical categories. The directionality of the relationship between sound and movement is not always fixed.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/Documents/in/Choreomusicology</ref> Choreomusicologists hold that studying the variable relationships between sound and movement in diverse performance arts can provide insight into perceptual sensibilities, cultural processes, and interpersonal dynamics. Famous artists whose works exhibit rich choreomusical relationships include: [[John Cage]] and [[Merce Cunningham]], [[Igor Stravinsky]] and [[George Balanchine]], and [[Louis Horst]] and [[Martha Graham]]. Interesting choreomusical relationships also exist in West Sumatran [[Tari Piring]], West Javanese [[Pencak Silat]], and Afro-Brazilian [[Capoeira]] to name but a few examples.<ref>http://jonathanstill.com/2012/03/02/new-choreomusicology-article/</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Mason | first1 = P.H. | year = 2012 | title = Music, dance and the total art work: choreomusicology in theory and practice | url = http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/14647893.2011.651116#preview | journal = Research in Dance Education | volume = 13 | issue = 1| pages = 5–24 | doi=10.1080/14647893.2011.651116}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1080/17411912.2014.926632 | volume=23 | title=Tapping the Plate or Hitting the Bottle: Sound and Movement in Self-accompanied and Musician-accompanied Dance | journal=Ethnomusicology Forum | pages=208–228}}</ref>
The following institutions have developed programs practicing and/or researching choreomusicology: [http://www.conservatoiredeparis.fr/disciplines/les-disciplines/les-disciplines-detail/discipline/accompagnement-choregraphique-1er-cycle-superieur/ accompagnement choregraphique] [[CNSMDP]] (Paris), [http://www.institutdelteatre.cat/ca/pl294/estudis/id47/curs-d-acompanyament-musical-del-moviment-en-les-arts-esceniques.htm continuing studies] at [http://www.institutdelteatre.cat/ Institut del Teatre] (Barcelona), [http://scenekunstskolen.dk/en/musical-accompaniment-dance-programme MAD] at [http://scenekunstskolen.dk/en/english-frontpage DNSPA] (Copenhagen). [http://www.consaq.it/offerta-formativa/maestro-collaboratore-per-la-danza.html MCD] at [http://www.accademianazionaledanza.it AND] (Rome - L'Aquila).
